Thanks for the video. Very informative. I had a 2003 S500 4-matic (4 doors, all wheel drive) with a V8. Very nice car.   Very quiet car.  Excellent acceleration with minimal gas pedal push.  Excellent surround sound audio system that one would think they were at a live concert (Bose sound system).  Ahead of the pack for the features they offered. I bought it used with 67,000 miles and drove it to 97,000 miles.  My opinion of Mercedes is that they offer a lot of features but the overall long term quality is lacking. They are very expensive to repair and the electronic features had lots of issues. Driver seat heater failed right after I bought it. Parts alone were $800 USD. I had to completely refurbish the front end suspension/steering mechanically. I had to repair the auto trunk open feature (hydraulic fluid mechanism). The ABS kept giving false failure modes due to at least four different sensors that could indicate the problem (and Mercedes didn't know which it could be and no refund it they replaced a sensor and it didn't fix the problem.   I would probably enjoy test driving the all electric EQS, but I think for the price it would take a longer manufacturer warranty (8 years, 100K miles across the board) for me to even consider buying another Mercedes. All of the high tech features are subject to early failure (from my experience) and Mercedes is definitely lagging when it comes to up-to-date software.  That said, the driving experience was like no other car I have ever owned.

I'm huge into tech, but I don't really trust electric cars. Hear me out: mechanical cars are great such that they don't rely on software or tech systems, you put your foot on the gas, and the car can run, on the brakes it stops (with very simple hydraulic control systems). However, these new electric cars have electrical motors and hardly any mechanical systems. I'm worried for bugs and glitches, and anything like that. What if the  system is overloaded with data, and putting your foot on the brakes does nothing? What if it freezes? What if someone hacks the cars? Therein lies my lack of trust. I could definitely deal with hybrid cars, but I can't put my life in the hand of objects that wholly rely on electrical systems. And for now, it's better for the environment to buy a used gas-car and run it until it breaks down, rather than an electric car: the amount of gas-waste of a gas-powered car, is less than the combined amount of production/manufacturing and electricity waste of buying a new electric-car

Karl Benz founded Mercedes.

Gottlieb Daimler and Karl Benz invented the automobile almost simultaneously in 1886, and their companies ended up merging in the early 20th century. For a long time the company was called Daimler-Benz, until it acquired or merged with Chrysler in the early 21st century, becoming DaimlerChrysler, before dropping Chrysler again and becoming Daimler AG (AG is the german equivalent of inc.).

So yes, Gottlieb Daimler was one of the founders. Karl Benz was the other one. Daimler's name simply ended up being the only one the company bears mostly by chance.

I think Tesla's time on the EV throne is soon coming to an end. Don't get me wrong, they still have the best software by far and are still leading in terms of battery tech but major manufacturers are catching up very quickly. In just the last few years, almost every major car manufacturer has come out with a decent EV option and they're learning very quickly. MKBHD asked whether it was more realistic for Tesla to become master craftsmen or whether Mercedes can become a software giant. Tesla is never going to have the build quality that a company like Mercedes has, they just don't care enough. On the other hand Mercedes can just outsource their software. Volvo already has an infotainment based on Android Auto and it's fantastic. I see no reason why Mercedes can't do something similar or just buy up a small software company to dedicate to that end of the equation. This is Mercedes' SECOND EV ever and they've made something truly great. Tesla will probably continue being a niche favorite for many people but they'll never beat the automotive behemoths with decades of experience because most people don't want a gadget on wheels, they want a better car, essentially an upgraded version of what they're used to.

"Can Mercedes make great software?"

My opinion: no, most car companies can't and shouldn't make software. Most car software is slow, with a mediocre touch screen, dated UI, bad UX, etc. At least that has always been my experience throughout the years. Tesla came to change a lot of that, as you mentioned, and I think that's a really cool thing. Imo, car companies should not be making software, they should be making cars and outsourcing software. If I'm not mistaken, Land Rover stopped making their own software a while ago (at least here in Germany) and made the great decision to outsource it (to Bosch, iirc). I have yet to see the results somewhere in the wild, but I did get to use the older one and it is BAD, probably worse than what we just saw from Mercedes in the EQS. That's just how I see it, I think car companies could really benefit from outsourcing it to people who know how to build proper software and can focus 100% on that.

I believe Tesla will catch up to the production quality of Mercedes faster than Mercedes can learn how to build great software and I have two points to make based on my experience as a product designer and consultant for tech companies, government and large and old organizations.

First point:
When developing a product, your typically in two camps, you're either trying to solve for a known challenges (like manufacturing) or you're trying to solve for an unknown challenge (like how do people want to interact with a car via software). Known problems can be challenging, but they're known and in many cases you can throw money and people at the problem. Unknown challenges are much harder because you're not even sure what the actual challenges may be and throwing more people and money at the challenge doesn't necessarily help you move faster. There is a lot of experimenting, testing, learning and iterating involved when solving for an unknown challenge.

Second point:
Culture plays a huge part into how quickly you're able to solve unknown challenges. Having worked with organizations that are large and set in their ways, the way they make decisions or deal with uncertainty can be very challenging to them. In these types of organizations, there is a lot of fear from employees and fear around failing which makes it hard to be "innovative". Another example is how they tend to work off of established specs because it's traditionally how these organizations operate. This means that decision makers decide on what the solution should look like and how it should function and the lower level employees are really just there to execute their plan.

In contrast, startups and most, but not all tech companies tend to be more agile. Meaning that they try a lot of different solutions and find the one that has the highest potential for success. Their culture allows them to fail and failing = learning which in return allow you to try again and again, but this time with more and more data to support your solution. Not to mention that these cultures also allow for constant iteration after release as you see very clearly with Tesla.

Conclusion:
Tesla may have not been able to meet the same quality levels as other car manufacturers, but getting there is a known problem. Other car manufacturers have solved this a long time ago and getting there may take time, but there are no many risks to finding a solution. Tesla has already shown that they have an agile mentality by how they have released and ittereated on their products way after giving them to customers.

On the flip side, Mercedes might be able to create an amazing looking and performing vehicle, but my assumption would be that because they are a much older and larger organization, their culture is probably outdated in many ways. Which then causes a lot of challenges internally when you're trying to solve an unknown challenge such as how do people want to interact with a vehicle via software.

That's just my two cents and as Marc Andreessen famously said "Software is eating the world", so my bet is on Tesla.

No, sorry, if that was no clear by me. It is the opposite in Europe (and only there): Teslas can charge at "all the other" chargers, but a Mercedes still not at a Tesla charger. But that is just Teslas decision. As I said, technically Tesla meanwhile uses the same plug as all the others - but Tesla doesn't allow that. Actually there was a bug with the superchargers last year that was spread on the internet, and so people charged their electric VW Golfs at the Tesla supercharger :-)

In the USA Tesla even uses anothe special plug. You can compare it a bit USB and Apple's Lightning Connector. So Everybody uses USB, it the standard. But only Apple uses its own plug. And so for electric cars, CCS is like USB. It is the standard. Every car maker uses CCS for their electric cars - only Tesla has its own plug. At least that is the situation in Europe, where CCS is more or less even pushed by laws. Japan had Chademo, China also has its own system. In the US tesla is very dominating.

So I don't know where you live, you have to look for your system there.

Depends on where you live. In Europe  we have much more CCS chargers than Tesla superchargers. But even Tesla accepted that CCS is the standard in Europe and switched to CCS. Which means, that they still have a big advantage, because they can use the General CCS chargers (like any other electric car) PLUS the Tesla Superchargers.

) The International Coalition to End Transplant Abuse in China (ETAC), one of the leading organizations aimed at ending the brutality of the Chinese Communist Party (CCP), recently held a conference on February 24 on the CCP‚Äôs forced organ harvesting.

In recent articles, we have covered several speakers at the event, such as Sir Geoffrey Nice QC (chair of China Tribunal) and Wendy Rogers (clinical ethics professor and one of Nature‚Äôs 10 people who mattered in science in 2019).

Here we focus on the speech by David Matas, human rights lawyer and author. Matas has led independent investigations on forced organ harvesting in China. His books include Bloody Harvest: The Killing of Falun Gong for Their Organs (2009), State Organs: Transplant Abuse in China (2012), and others.

During his speech at the ETAC forum, Matas elaborated on the possible actions to end forced organ harvesting from a legal perspective. He called for more specific laws targeting the CCP. For example, based on Magnitsky legislation, various governments could add criminals involved in organ harvesting to their respective lists of human rights violators to be sanctioned. Moreover, professional organizations and individuals who participated in the atrocity should be excluded and isolated. Finally, reports on organ tourism should be provided by each country to assess the severity of the issue for further actions.


David Matas speaks at the International Coalition to End Transplant Abuse in China (ETAC) conference on February 24, 2021.

Magnitsky Legislation
How to make laws applicable to stop organ harvesting in China? Matas thinks the CCP's laws are meaningless because the CCP controls the law-making process and only enacts and enforces laws that target others, but not the CCP itself. In other words, the CCP would not use its laws to stop itself from committing the crime of organ harvesting.

As a result, other nations should have local laws that ban forced organ harvesting activities. Such laws, once implemented, would curb the CCP to some extent. But they may not be sufficient since only limited information is available from China.

For example, the CCP has been raising funds for the military healthcare system through selling organs, but it has vehemently denied the fact. Therefore, general laws are important, but they may not get us far.

A more effective approach is coming up with laws that specifically target the CCP. The more tailored such laws are in spelling out how the CCP has committed crimes, the more effective they would be.

One good example is the Magnitsky legislation. It exists in many countries but hasn't been widely adopted. Under this law, human rights violators risk having their identities publicized, being barred from entering countries with Magnitsky legislation, and having their assets frozen in such countries.

In many countries, the Magnitsky legislation has been applied to various kinds of human rights perpetrators, but not those involved in organ harvesting in China. Therefore, we should request that countries that have such laws add organ harvesting criminals to Magnitsky sanction lists.

The problem with a tech-heavy car like this one is the same problem every tech-heavy car in history has had: within a few years everything will be dated and obsolete. The more tech features you stuff into a car, the faster this happens. This is often made worse by the long gestation periods for cars. Engineering for a car like this would have started many years ago, meaning that by the time the car was production ready it was already a few years out of date from a tech perspective. The screens, voice response, tablet etc in a car like this is going to be ridiculously aged in five years. In this regard, I think Tesla has it right: keep car features simple and software-based, update the software frequently.

EQS hands down. But the tech side was always a problem for car makers. I think Tesla is the first one to make proper infotainment in a car. BMW, Mercedes, VW, Renault, Seat, Ford, Toyota (omg, its so bad!), Mazda, they all do the absolute worse in terms of software and what is this software put on.

That tablet at the back, that S Tab4, is there because a car is designed for YEARS, it was designed that 7 years ago, with that tablet being "top dog" back then. You may ask, why is Tesla using the best and newest then? Simple. They first make a car, get the general interior (that is very simple, keep it in mind!) and then when the car is already almost in production, they design the electronics. Any other car manufacturer goes area after an area of the car, and when they design interior - well, it may be 7 years before the car is out on the road. In tech world that's 6-8 generations of products, and each made a gigantic leap in it's performance.

I think for right now, gas version. Electric is great and all and has so many advantages, but outside of the Tesla network in the US, electrical charging infrastructure is nowhere near as large as gas power infrastructure. A lot of people can only charge their cars at home. Yes electric cars have comparable ranges, but that range is virtually halved when you consider a lot of people can only go so far cos they need to keep charge to get home and charge.

That being said, a hybrid version, that would make all the most sense in a goobal perspective cos they can be plugged in and run well on electric alone in places like China, Europe and the US, and can run in less advanced places where only fuel oils are available like in Africa, South America and eastern Europe. The cars run and charge themselves using gas, eventually running in hybrid mode or even electric mode from time to time. This then results in lower field consumption with fuel actually being consumed being done so very economically. It's a win win for everyone.

Electrics are great and all, but hybrids are better for right now as a transitional vehicle while the world gets its infrastructure and battery production up to par.

The thing is, software is difficult and if you're not investing significant amounts of money into really good software engineers and making it a core part of the company, you will not be successful. I don't think that Mercedes-Benz is that far off the mark in terms of ability to build software, but they just need better UX engineers who work at crafting beautiful, fluid and intuitive experiences with the software in the car. I've always found Mercedes-Benz interiors to be unintuitive.
Also the performance of the software is really important and from everything I've seen, all of the interactions are really laggy and that's probably because the car is doing too many network calls rather than the performance of the onboard computer. If you can get the car to rely on the internet less and really work on tuning the performance of the software to where a touch response is instant, that'll make the experience so much better.

Would pick the gas version probably at first. Don't think Mercedes, BMW, VW, or Tesla have come to a point where electric cars have the flexibility of gas cars. I'm living in Germany and there is still not enough infrastructure for electric drive, not from Tesla's side but also not from the governments. Different paying Systems that are making you crazy, not working Charging Stations, Problems with the organization at one point - living in the Outback is a pain in the ass, where distances are huge. Going to the supermarket, doctor's appointment or just to work can easily become a 60km ride in one way, and you really can't get a normal week with a Tesla, where the fastest charging station is taking a full day or at least 12 hours to charge fully.
And in the second, most important, electric cars are not better for the environment at all. The Engines, and, most important the battery made out of Lithium is worse than driving Diesel for 200000 kilometers! So if you get a Tesla because of environmental points, you need to drive it for at least 4x times longer than a Diesel/Gas Car to make it viable. And charge it from REAL green and economic electricity, that does not come from Coal mines in the Czech Republic or Poland. You can't prove it, you have no infrastructure, batteries are way too small, you need to bring a lot of time with you. That's why I hate the Diesel hate here in Germany, Diesel is the most efficient, reliable, and profitable fuel in the world for now.

I happen to work in the software development in the automotive section in Germany, and you have just captured in less than 20 minutes the core of our problem here. The German methodology if software development is oriented in a totally different direction than making a more polished interface for the user interface. From my perspective Tesla as much as i hate to admit it might catch up on the quality side faster than Germany catching up on software interface. Yet, don't get me wrong, the other aspects of the software, other than the interface, might be a million times better. Talking about motor management ECU battery management, chassis control abs esp and so on. All these aspects of a vehicle also require some level of software controlling and monitoring the car vitals and kinematics.
In this kind of software, I believe our, German, product is really superior.
Only when it comes to interface the Germans drop the ball. This fact is not only visible in automotive, compare a samsung TV to a blaupunkt TV, compare an LG cloth iron to a Bosch clothes iron.

I'd rather go with a gasoline car. There are many reasons for that:

First of all, i think e-cars are not there where they can be, hardware and software wise. On the hardware departement, you need to make sacrifices in favor of building a stronger car. For example an S-Class in gasoline is much more bigger and wider build than an e-car and has much more power compared to the e version. This goes also for sportcars. In favor of building a fast e-sport car, they shrink it in size, so some of them come in ridiculously small size form inside and outside the car. And also the longevity of lithium batteries are not as great as it could or should be for me to consider to buy an e-car yet. Software wise, i have many issues with using an e-car yet. First, AI is not as advanced as it makes a big difference to use an e-car. Second, electronics tend to have software issues and bugs all the time. When this happens as customer, youre pretty much in the hand of one company, who should fix it. Till then you cant do nothing by yourself. That means you need to sacrifice your authonomy to handle your car by yourself or fix it whereever you want it. If you have a problem with your car, you probably cant go to any garage to let your car fixed. Like all the electronic devices you possibly need to go to special places and the car parts would be possibly more expensive and also services for fixing the car. third, im not sure about that, but if you need to login somehow for using the car. Then you need to consider, that some company will have access of all the data about your usage of the car. If police would have access to these data, then it would make the way of racial profiling probably worst. And also i think, e-cars tend to get aged much more quicker than not regular cars, so everything you buy feels more like a beta version of what it should be. Personally i give more value to longevity for environmental reasons. If theres no option for you, to not buy a car, then i try to use the same car as longer as in can before i buy a new car. With an e-car it would be possibly more difficult to use the same car for longer period of time.

Second, charging stations are not everywhere. Tesla has the biggest network in this regard. If you using an electro car, you would be pretty much in the hands of one ore two companies who run all the charging stations. They could change the prices whenever they like to. This goes also for gasoline prices of course, but i think this is little bit different, because everyone can open a gas station, and it works for every car. But charging stations are like charging cable from old phones, you can only use that one charging network for your brand of car. Therefore youll be in the monopoly of that one company, who owns that entire network. Maybe itll change int the future. But im talking from the point of now. For now its pretty much tesla and tesla only. I dont want to put myself into this situation i am totally dependend on decisions of one single company. And also there is a possibility, but im not sure, that the price of charging your car could change in different locations, because the cost of electricity is different. In this regard, i also want to give the example of the incident in Texas. If prices of electricity goes up, you cant charge and use your car until its fixed. So you cant estimate the cost of your trip as efficient as you could with a gasoline car.

Third, from production to recycling, batteries are not necessarily an environmentally friendlier option than gasoline cars. So whit all the cons i dont see it makes a sense to switch to an e-car yet.

While this car is very impressive for sure, I can't help but feel that this car has a little too many features for its price point, and I'll tell you what I mean. Let's consider the Lucid Air (in the GT trim), which should be the same price as this car, around 130k. It has less features, for example it doesn't have auto closing doors or separate bluetooth connections per seat or what have you, but I noticed that the material quality on the Air is superior to this EQS, there is noticeably less plastic in the Air and a complete lack of this terrible piano gloss plastic that you'd see in a Camry these days. Moreover, the audio system for example in Air doesn't have as many features, it's just a nice audio system, but it has high quality speaker drivers and is Dolby Atmos compatible, something Lucid is premiering as a world's first in a car. Additionally, given that this car is an electric S-Class, Mercedes will have engineered all of the features the same way they would be in an S-Class or other cars they make. For example, in a Mercedes the door lock system is a totally separate system from the rest of the systems and operates independently, same goes for the massaging seats (although these may have changed) or the power windows or maybe even that mirror adjusting system. This means that there are a million separate systems working in the car instead of doing the more efficient thing and routing all the signals through the central ECU/Infotainment computer, hell, I bet even the ECU and the Infotainment computer are separate elements in this car. Tesla for example runs all of the car's functions through the central computer, making for much simpler manufacturing, theoretically more reliable systems, and easier repair. I imagine given what I know about the Lucid Air that they took a similar approach to Tesla with that car. Why does Mercedes do this you might ask, and it's a legitimate question. Well, it's so they can shaft you as soon as you take it in to the mechanic when something breaks. It's one of the reasons that S-Classes on the used market depreciate incredibly quickly while Toyotas and Model 3's hold their value much better.

I see two different engineering philosophies here between Lucid and Mercedes. Mercedes I would argue has built a bit of an American car here, lots of features but each of lower quality. Whereas Lucid went the other way and has less features but each one is built stronger and likely more reliably. The way I see it, the EQS is a car you'd lease to impress your friends, whereas the Air is the one you'd want to own.

I have to disagree with you Marques. I don‚Äôt believe that large luxury cars like this are the perfect type of car to go electric now. Big, fancy, luxury sedans are the least important to go electric imo. The average car buyer can‚Äôt afford a vehicle like this, which means it‚Äôs not contributing much to convert the industry to electric. Affordable cars that the masses will buy, such as Corollas and Civic are the most important to go electric. Those will convert the entire industry very quickly. Luxury vehicles like this which are unattainable to most won‚Äôt do anything.
In addition, with electric cars, efficiency is the most important thing. You want the most range possible, and a huge ‚Äúboat to drive‚Äù like this is not going to get as much range as a small, light car. Also, because charging problems and range anxiety are still a thing, electric cars aren‚Äôt ideal for long distances, which means that they are better for around town. Daily cars for getting around town are better off being smaller and more nimble. I believe manufacturers really should focus on affordable electric cars. There‚Äôs too many luxury options now and it‚Äôs causing the switch to electric to take far longer than it should.

To answer your question about taking this car in electric or gas, at this time I would take it in the gas version. For a big car like this I‚Äôd want it to be good for long trips and currently electrics aren‚Äôt good for trips. When the charging problems are emitted (battery swapping stations, longer range, battery life cycle and efficiency improvements) then I would take the electric version. For all that to happen, we need the entire industry to switch to electric, and only making luxury cars isn‚Äôt going to do that.

I actually don't think either will happen. Mercedes will not become a tech company since its buyers are already happy with its infotainment system. In fact this is the same interface as the new S class. People buying a Mercedes will buy it regardless of the tech. 90% of people don't really care about the pixel density of the screen or the usability of the interface. Tesla will not improve in terms of luxury since a) They do not have the resources. Right now it's all hands on deck just meeting expected demand and expanding to new countries. b) They have a long way to catch up in terms of build quality before they can even start focusing on luxury. Given how long overdue a refresh is across their lineup, it doesn't look like they can afford to make any changes to their production line. c) They have to meet their lofty promises of the sports car, the semi, and the cybertruck. They must do that before switching focus to interior quality.

In terms of the other question, i'd rather have the gas powered S class until the EQS range is north of 750 miles. After that, for an S class, electric hands down.

I have to say something: an automobile is not a computer. An automobile must offer the highest quality of workmanship, safety and comfort. This also means that the materials used for the body, for the wheel suspension, for the dampers and for the engines must be very durable, trouble-free and, above all, fit for all purposes. As a driver, I want maximum ride comfort, excellent build quality and perfect precision in the engines and powertrain. A car has to be economical to drive, quiet inside and out, and make my ride as pleasant as possible. Nothing must rattle, clatter and rumble. When I drive a car, I don't care at all about over-the-top gimmicks in the software - and I even find these gimmicks annoying and distracting. I want to keep my eyes on the road and on the passing landscape - and not constantly on a screen.

Absolutely sick car. I agree with most everything you said in terms of it's pros and the cons it has. The big cons being "really? A Galaxy Tab 4?" and the overall software not being great. But i think they NAILED everything else, all those things Mercedes is already known to be great at. The question of will Tesla get better at fit/finish or will Mercedes get good at software first i think is really interesting and i honestly think it's a toss up. Mercedes has what is arguably the "easier" thing to play catch up in. Good software just requires UI designers and coders who know what they're doing and a good vision. On the surface at least. In reality that's way easier said than done. You can spend YEARS iterating on software before it really is great. It will really depend on their team they hire. Tesla i think has a big uphill battle with fit/finish. But i think they are already working up that hill, they get better and better with quality as time goes on and as they bring more factories online and as they have less "production hell" to deal with. However, i think they may have backed themselves into a minimalism corner. At a certain point, it's not about fit and finish and more about the customers still having a huge preference for tons of buttons and knobs and other trappings of what people are used to car interiors being like. Tesla purposefully going against that style of car interior will always be a knock against getting a Tesla for those people. But i think the EV space is big enough for the both of them and competition between the two of them will only make them both better.

To the final question of would you have this EQS or the gas version, it comes down like always to range. Sure, it has a 107 kWh battery and a very impressive Cx, but it's a big ass car that may weight more than 2.5-2.6 tonnes, so unless the motors that they're going to use are near as efficient as the ones Tesla uses in the Model S, I have my doubts. And after this, just like every other single electric car apart from Tesla, the charging infrastructure is very poor. Yeah, it sure is expandind, but the charging fees are way more expensive (yeah, not a problem for someone spending probably 150k at least on a car) and there are wayyy less fast chargers. If you're only buying the car to drive (or to be driven) around a big city without leaving that area that much, then this EQS is just better in every single way than the gas version. If you're planing on doing long trips, I honestly doubt it even if they advertise 600km range, we've all seen that a billion times
